    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-07T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-07T19:00:00-05:00" n="243"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d243">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">845.01/7–744: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Officer in Charge at New Delhi</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Merrell</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-07T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 7, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>467. Please inform Department of present status of matter discussed in
                    Department’s 427 of June 16. Drew Pearson’s<note n="17" xml:id="d243fn17">Drew
                        Pearson was the writer of a syndicated newspaper column.</note> column of
                    July 6 featured a story on this subject. There is some indication that he
                    received his information from Indian nationals in the United States. Does the
                    Mission believe that the existence of the letters in question could have been
                    made known by Indian Congress circles to sympathizers in the United States.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
